\subtree{
\title{5. Physical Social Engineering}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Tailgating}: Badge-controlled entrances without mantraps or visual}
\li{\strong{Badge cloning}: Proximity card technology (125kHz HID is trivially cloned).}
\li{\strong{Impersonation}: Delivery, maintenance, IT support pretexts for physical}
\li{\strong{Dumpster diving}: Document disposal procedures, shredding policy.}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Audit Methodology}
\p{Execute in order. Each step informs the next.}

\p{\strong{Step 1: Map human-mediated authentication paths.} Enumerate every path where a human (support agent, IT admin, manager) can override, bypass, or supplement automated authentication. Document what each path can do and what verification it requires.}

\p{\strong{Step 2: Identify identity verification procedures.} For each human-mediated path: what questions are asked? What constitutes "sufficient" proof of identity? Is it documented or ad hoc? Can the answers be obtained via OSINT?}

\p{\strong{Step 3: Assess OSINT exposure.} Gather publicly available information that could be used to answer verification questions or craft targeted pretexts. Focus on: employee names and roles, email formats, technology stack, org structure, breached credentials.}

\p{\strong{Step 4: Evaluate phishing controls.} Check email authentication records (SPF/DKIM/DMARC). Enumerate registered lookalike domains. Review whether the organization has phishing-resistant MFA (WebAuthn/FIDO2) or phishable MFA (TOTP/SMS).}

\p{\strong{Step 5: Review account recovery flows.} Walk through every account recovery path as an attacker who controls only public information. Identify which paths leak user existence, accept guessable answers, or defer to a human who can be pretexted.}

\p{\strong{Step 6: Test help desk resistance.} Design pretext scenarios based on Steps 2-3. Assess (or recommend testing) whether support staff follow verification procedures under pressure, urgency, or authority cues.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Code Review Patterns}
\p{When reviewing application source, flag these patterns:}

\subtree{
\title{User Enumeration}
\pre{\startverb
# BAD: Different responses for valid vs invalid users
if not user_exists(email):
    return "No account found"     # Leaks existence
return "Reset link sent"
\stopverb}

\p{Fix: Return the same response regardless. Send email only if account exists.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Security Questions for Recovery}
\p{Any use of security questions (mother's maiden name, first pet, etc.) is a finding. These are OSINT-retrievable and not secrets.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Support Tooling Without Verification Audit Trail}
\pre{\startverb
# BAD: Support action with no identity verification logged
@admin_required
def reset_user_password(user_id):
    user.set_random_password()    # No record of what verification was performed
\stopverb}

\p{Fix: Require and log the verification method used before any support action.}
}

\subtree{
\title{OAuth/SSO Misconfigurations}
\ul{
\li{Open redirect in OAuth callback URLs (enables token theft)}
\li{Wildcard or overly broad redirect URI matching}
\li{Missing \code{\startverb state\stopverb} parameter validation (CSRF in OAuth flow)}
\li{Auto-approval of OAuth consent for internal apps (can be abused if app}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Rate Limiting Gaps}
\pre{\startverb
# BAD: No rate limit on verification code endpoint
@app.route("/verify-code", methods=["POST"])
def verify_code():
    if request.form["code"] == stored_code:
        grant_access()
\stopverb}

\p{Fix: Rate limit by IP and account. Lock after N failures. Use longer codes.}
}

\subtree{
\title{MFA Bypass in Recovery}
\p{Look for code paths where MFA is enforced at login but skipped during account recovery, password reset, or support-initiated access.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Output Format}
\p{Structure findings as:}

\pre{\startverb
### [SE-001] Finding Title

Severity: Critical / High / Medium / Low / Informational
Category: Pretexting | Auth Bypass | OSINT Exposure | Phishing | Physical
Attack Scenario: Concrete, step-by-step description of how an attacker
  exploits this. Name the pretext. Name the channel. Name what they obtain.
Evidence: What was observed (code path, policy gap, DNS record, etc.)
Remediation: Specific, actionable fix. Not "improve training."
References: Relevant standards (NIST 800-63B, OWASP, etc.)
\stopverb}

\p{Severity calibration:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Critical}: Direct account takeover via social channel, no technical skill required.}
\li{\strong{High}: Account takeover possible with moderate OSINT gathering.}
\li{\strong{Medium}: Information disclosure that enables targeted attacks.}
\li{\strong{Low}: Weak controls that increase attack surface but require chaining.}
\li{\strong{Informational}: Observations that inform security posture but lack direct exploit path.}
}
}

